	('12242116-7ffa-43c1-9a1a-38564b08879a', '6521b4af-de4e-4a3d-a67e-b9ae8ad93277', 'high_school_adaptive_core_d1_logical_reasoning_1768625690289_1wia3x', 'D', false, 4531, 1, 'logical_reasoning', 'adaptive_core', 22, '2026-01-27 06:49:54.196836+00', 'Priya notices that every time she wears her red scarf, it rains the next day. She has worn her red scarf three times this month, and it has rained the next day each time. What can Priya logically conclude?', '{"A": "Her red scarf causes rain", "B": "Wearing her red scarf is a reliable predictor of rain", "C": "The scarf has no connection to the weather", "D": "She should stop wearing the scarf to prevent rain"}', 'C', 'This is a classic correlation vs. causation fallacy. Just because two events happen together doesn''t mean one causes the other. The scarf and rain could be coincidental, or there could be other factors (like seasonal weather patterns). Logical reasoning requires avoiding unwarranted causal conclusions from limited observations.'),
	('5723366e-0452-4ce7-b89d-0cc6248a38b2', '6521b4af-de4e-4a3d-a67e-b9ae8ad93277', 'high_school_adaptive_core_d1_pattern_recognition_1768625391248_3wypb3', 'D', false, 1741, 1, 'pattern_recognition', 'adaptive_core', 23, '2026-01-27 06:49:57.807899+00', 'Look at this number pattern: 3, 6, 12, 24, 48, ________. What number comes next?', '{"A": "72", "B": "96", "C": "60", "D": "52"}', 'B', 'Each number is double the previous one: 48 × 2 = 96.'),
