	('f6275309-7279-4fc6-b4ca-a54290cb0509', 'd545657b-c54a-4e17-90c3-00e619965517', 'middle_school_adaptive_core_d1_data_interpretation_1769891166114_qo1eqz', 'B', false, 2237, 1, 'data_interpretation', 'adaptive_core', 35, '2026-01-31 20:26:08.810477+00', 'A class has 18 students. If 10 of them are girls, how many are boys?', '{"A": "8", "B": "10", "C": "12", "D": "6"}', 'A', 'There are 18 students total, and if 10 are girls, then 18 - 10 = 8 boys.'),
	('c14ee315-827a-4c64-90ec-9517c81352c1', 'd0f35510-1e79-4bee-8b0e-b581f62bf9ae', 'middle_school_diagnostic_d3_data_interpretation_1769754696932_y9dok7', 'B', false, 1144, 3, 'data_interpretation', 'diagnostic_screener', 4, '2026-02-02 05:38:55.824419+00', 'A survey of 120 students found that 45 liked reading, 30 liked writing, and 20 liked both. How many students liked either reading or writing?', '{"A": "45", "B": "50", "C": "55", "D": "65"}', 'D', 'Using the principle of inclusion-exclusion: students who like reading or writing = (students who like reading) + (students who like writing) - (students who like both) = 45 + 30 - 20 = 55, but since the question asks for ''either'', we should consider those who like only one of them and add back those who like both once, hence it actually directly translates to 45 + 30 - 20 = 55'),
	('6a283905-45af-4c3d-8367-2f1020c6d087', 'd0f35510-1e79-4bee-8b0e-b581f62bf9ae', 'middle_school_diagnostic_d3_spatial_reasoning_1769754696932_2qnwqv', 'C', false, 2077, 3, 'spatial_reasoning', 'diagnostic_screener', 5, '2026-02-02 05:38:58.222233+00', 'Imagine a cube with each side being 6 units long. What is the volume of this cube?', '{"A": "60 cubic units", "B": "120 cubic units", "C": "180 cubic units", "D": "216 cubic units"}', 'D', 'The volume of a cube is calculated by cubing the length of one side: 6^3 = 216 cubic units'),
	('933bed07-c399-4d85-adb4-534b585f237c', 'd0f35510-1e79-4bee-8b0e-b581f62bf9ae', 'middle_school_adaptive_core_d2_spatial_reasoning_1769754926058_fzp0c1', 'B', true, 1338, 2, 'spatial_reasoning', 'adaptive_core', 9, '2026-02-02 05:39:10.864565+00', 'A rectangular picture frame has a length of 18 inches and a width of 12 inches. If it is placed on a wall with its length horizontal, what is the smallest possible area of the wall that can completely cover the frame?', '{"A": "180 square inches", "B": "216 square inches", "C": "240 square inches", "D": "270 square inches"}', 'B', 'To find the smallest area, the frame''s length and width must align with the wall''s dimensions. Since the frame''s length is 18 inches and its width is 12 inches, the smallest area that can cover it is 18 * 12 = 216 square inches.'),
	('22587af3-ba08-4b3d-8dce-a5150c8c77cc', 'd0f35510-1e79-4bee-8b0e-b581f62bf9ae', 'middle_school_core_d3_numerical_reasoning_1769754776834_ljsp2j', 'C', false, 1264, 3, 'numerical_reasoning', 'adaptive_core', 10, '2026-02-02 05:39:12.803902+00', 'A water tank can hold 2400 liters of water. If 1200 liters of water are already in the tank, what fraction of the tank is filled?', '{"A": "1/4", "B": "1/2", "C": "3/4", "D": "2/3"}', 'B', 'Since 1200 liters out of 2400 liters is filled, the fraction filled is 1200/2400 = 1/2'),
