	('5febd92f-1e2b-4320-b8be-fc94e52fbd95', '0ede676a-04f8-4a2f-b944-38dfb9a812b6', 'higher_secondary_diagnostic_d3_logical_reasoning_1769896515271_po2rci', 'C', true, 5273, 3, 'logical_reasoning', 'diagnostic_screener', 8, '2026-01-31 21:56:17.60544+00', 'What is the missing number in the series: 3, 8, 15, 24, __, 40?', '{"A": "30", "B": "31", "C": "32", "D": "33"}', 'C', 'The series adds consecutive odd numbers, so the missing number is 24+8=32.'),
	('e37e6898-20a9-4e13-b35b-5c86beee16a2', '9861d060-4fe8-4e5d-8fb6-085e651961b5', 'middle_school_diagnostic_d3_numerical_reasoning_1769768724954_3diojg', 'C', true, 18628, 3, 'numerical_reasoning', 'diagnostic_screener', 1, '2026-02-02 10:27:18.562828+00', 'A farmer has 45 chickens and sells 1/3 of them. How many chickens does the farmer have left?', '{"A": "10", "B": "15", "C": "30", "D": "40"}', 'C', '1/3 of 45 is 45/3 = 15. The farmer sold 15 chickens, so he has 45 - 15 = 30 chickens left.'),
	('873099ad-bc15-4a6a-845b-cfde81f5b569', '9861d060-4fe8-4e5d-8fb6-085e651961b5', 'middle_school_diagnostic_d3_logical_reasoning_1769768519128_3t75bi', 'B', true, 9775, 3, 'logical_reasoning', 'diagnostic_screener', 4, '2026-02-02 10:27:46.038227+00', 'If all cats like fish and Mittens is a cat, then which of the following must be true?', '{"A": "Mittens likes birds.", "B": "Mittens likes fish.", "C": "All animals like fish.", "D": "Mittens is a dog."}', 'B', 'The statement ''all cats like fish'' and ''Mittens is a cat'' leads to the conclusion that Mittens likes fish.'),
	('c2ed84d5-e302-4671-b4bd-dc459c2c504d', '9861d060-4fe8-4e5d-8fb6-085e651961b5', 'middle_school_stability_confirmation_d3_pattern_recognition_1770029142212_h53jh7', 'A', false, 142850, 1, 'pattern_recognition', 'stability_confirmation', 18, '2026-02-02 10:48:05.246703+00', 'What comes next: A, B, C, D, ?', '{"A": "F", "B": "E", "C": "G", "D": "A"}', 'B', 'Fallback question'),
	('bafc2cba-0d3b-4137-9b68-ef23b7e6921b', '0ede676a-04f8-4a2f-b944-38dfb9a812b6', 'higher_secondary_diagnostic_d3_logical_reasoning_1769896515271_kvytol', 'B', false, 3290, 3, 'logical_reasoning', 'diagnostic_screener', 2, '2026-01-31 21:55:24.553993+00', 'Which number comes next in the sequence: 2, 5, 10, 17, 26, ...?', '{"A": "33", "B": "36", "C": "37", "D": "40"}', 'C', 'The sequence adds consecutive odd numbers, so next is 26+11=37.'),
	('993e0e81-84fb-466f-b4b8-299c5ad89920', '0ede676a-04f8-4a2f-b944-38dfb9a812b6', 'higher_secondary_diagnostic_d3_pattern_recognition_1769896515271_al3i14', 'D', false, 6951, 3, 'pattern_recognition', 'diagnostic_screener', 6, '2026-01-31 21:56:06.455037+00', 'If A=1, B=2, C=3, and D=4, what is the value of BAD in this coding system?', '{"A": "7", "B": "8", "C": "9", "D": "10"}', 'B', 'Adding the values of B, A, and D gives 2+1+4=7.'),
	('c0b428bd-635f-4d3e-a328-446bdbaab4aa', '9861d060-4fe8-4e5d-8fb6-085e651961b5', 'middle_school_diagnostic_d3_data_interpretation_1769768724954_3yzmez', 'C', true, 10392, 3, 'data_interpretation', 'diagnostic_screener', 2, '2026-02-02 10:27:30.133992+00', 'The table shows the number of rainy days in a town for four months: April (8 days), May (6 days), June (4 days), July (2 days). Which month had twice as many rainy days as July?', '{"A": "April", "B": "May", "C": "June", "D": "July"}', 'C', 'July had 2 rainy days. Twice that amount is 2 * 2 = 4 rainy days, which occurred in June.'),
	('b0747042-a85b-44a6-b533-92771ffd9cdb', '9861d060-4fe8-4e5d-8fb6-085e651961b5', 'middle_school_adaptive_core_d5_data_interpretation_1770028399221_fapbcw', 'A', false, 143698, 5, 'data_interpretation', 'adaptive_core', 13, '2026-02-02 10:35:43.429084+00', 'In a class of 20 students, 8 like soccer and 12 like basketball. How many more students like basketball than soccer?', '{"A": "2", "B": "4", "C": "6", "D": "8"}', 'B', 'Fallback question'),
	('1eaadf25-cd29-4452-ba0a-40161b498515', '9861d060-4fe8-4e5d-8fb6-085e651961b5', 'middle_school_adaptive_core_d4_logical_reasoning_1769769209290_ipd9kg', 'A', false, 157981, 4, 'logical_reasoning', 'adaptive_core', 14, '2026-02-02 10:38:23.272005+00', 'Leo, Mia, and Noah are practicing musical instruments. Leo plays either the trumpet or the drums. Mia plays either the flute or the piano. Noah plays either the guitar or the drums. If Leo is playing the trumpet, then Noah is playing the guitar. What can you conclude?', '{"A": "If Noah is playing the drums, then Leo is playing the trumpet.", "B": "If Leo is playing the drums, then Noah is playing the guitar.", "C": "If Noah is playing the guitar, then Leo is playing the drums.", "D": "If Leo is playing the drums, then Noah is playing the drums."}', 'D', 'We know that if Leo plays the trumpet, Noah plays the guitar. This means if Noah is NOT playing the guitar, Leo is NOT playing the trumpet. Since Noah only plays either guitar or drums, if Leo is playing the drums, then Noah is playing the drums.'),
